The properties of layers of maps created with tIDE are not stored. To get the name and the visibility status, I had to add the following lines after TiledMapTileLayer layer = new TiledMapTileLayer(layerSizeX, layerSizeY, tileSizeX, tileSizeY):
    layer.setName(id);
    layer.setVisible(visible.equalsIgnoreCase("true"));

It would be better, if the SelectBox store Objects and not Strings. So you can show a Value and use another value in hour app.

For example I can use the following class as an array for the SelectBox.

class SelectBoxItems {
  private String key;
  private String value;

  public SelectBoxItem(String key, String value) {
    this.key = key;
    this.value = value;
  }

  public String getKey() {
    return key;
  }

  @Override
  public String toString() {
    return value;
  }
}

Hi,

I don't know if this would be called a bug but, I have a case where I have an enum like this;

```
public enum ToneType {
    SubSynth("subsynth"),
...
}
```

Then I have a class with 2 constructors;

```
    private ToneType toneType;

    public SubSynthTone() {
        super(ToneType.SubSynth, null);
    }

    public SubSynthTone(ICaustkController controller) {
        super(ToneType.SubSynth, controller);
    }
```

This second gets called by my framework, the first by Json deserialization.

What is happening is when the SubSynthTone is serialized, Line 244 in Json is thinking the field is a defaultValue and continues.

I didn't know that when you pass an enum in a super() statement it's considered default.

The problem is, the toneType field doesn't get put into the json string, so when I wakeup the new tone from the String, I don't have a toneType to switch on to create the correct tone instance.

Do you think this is a bug in the defaultSerialization code? Or should I just pass null in the default constructor's super() call.

PS I am using a JsonReader to get the toneType from the data string;

```
    public static ToneType readToneType(String data) throws IOException {
        JsonValue value = new JsonReader().parse(data);
        JsonValue next = value.get("toneType");
        if (next != null)
            return ToneType.valueOf(next.asString());
        return null;
    }
```

Mike
